<br>
If I'd made Everquest I would have made the game without classes and used a similar skill/spell type of system as Elder Scrolls: Morrowind.  This allows you to build spells - if you are smart enough to learn them, powerful enough to be allowed by the guild to know the basis of them, and rich enough to try.<br>
<br>
The thing you have to realize though is that Rogues aren't Rogues in Everquest, they are Ninjas, or assassins at best.  You can't call upon other games' definition for the class, because they just don't apply here.<br>
<br>
When I made my rogue, I wanted him to be like Garret in Thief (HIGHLY recommended game) but I knew better, there's no way in Everquest you'll be able to climb a wall, sneak past guards, pick a lock to a chest, steal the widget and knock something out from behind, dragging the body to cover so you can make your escape.  Everquest doesn't have a clever enough engine and the game can't sustain the 'chest full of treasure' concept because of camping.<br>
<br>
You have to admit that just about every fantasy game in existence has knock and disarm trap type spells in the repertoire, but that's balanced by other factors (such as the ones I suggested, in addition to making Rogue type characters a much more feasible and useful class without killing things).<br>
<br>
The thing is, the fact that there's so few locked doors that are even worth unlocking really should give you a hint to how immensely minor something like this would be.  Your desire is to defend what makes a Rogue a rogue, but picking locks and disarming traps isn't what MAKES you a Rogue in Everquest.  Rogues in Everquest are sneaky murderers, your pick pocket ability is even nearly worthless.  Giving up a marginal and as you admitted nearly insignificant ability in a poorer, more limited form to another class wouldn't even cause a hiccup to Rogues.  I mean you are aware Bards get both skills right?<br>
<br>
But the discussion is moot... it won't happen and even if it did, it would mean nothing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=swipey>Swipey</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 137<br> <font color=#ffffff>(10/23/02 11:01 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ..</span><hr size=1> Bards have always had something of a roguely air about them.<br>
<br>
And it is valid, IMO, to bring up other sources than just EQ when talking about what people want or expect in the game.  Who ever heard of &quot;orcs&quot; or &quot;halflings&quot; before tolkein, and especially before D&amp;D?  Both those are quite obviously source material for norrath, even if it is officially uncredited.<br>
<br>
<br>
I would LOVE to see a non-class based or only inclination based game where all skills are available to all characters, with enopugh development.  At its most basic (I alluded to this in another thread (or maybe earlier in this one!)) one that had only 3 skill trees that were not mutually exclusive.<br>
<br>
Physical, Arcane, and Religious.  At character creation, each player ranks these three, 1 to 3, in the order of his characters inclinations toward them.  <br>
<br>
A classic big, dumb warrior type would have Physical 1,  Religious 2, and Arcane 3.<br>
A classic bookish, indoorsy wizard type, Arcane 1, Religious 2, and Physical 3.<br>
And the classic &quot;cleric&quot; type, Religious 1, Physical 2, Arcane 3.<br>
<br>
How these work is as multipliers on the cost of developing skills in each tree.  A big, dumb warrior learns physical skills easily, but bookish ones are very hard.  Not that he cant learn them, they just take 3 times the effort as an equivalent physical skill.  He is naturally athletic, but gets restless if he has to sit still for hours on end reading some boring ol book.<br>
<br>
A slightly more complex system would involve ranking each area 3, 6, or 9, and then, within each area, having strenghts and weaknesses represented by modifying the area ranking by -1, +1, or leaving it alone, with all -1s needing to be balanced by +1s.<br>
<br>
<br>
A Big Dumb Warrior might distribute his physical rankings as follows :<br>
<br>
Overall : 3<br>
Strength (2)<br>
Finesse (4)<br>
Endurance (3)<br>
<br>
Whereas a rogue :<br>
Overall : 3<br>
Strength (3)<br>
Finesse (2)<br>
Endurance (4)<br>
<br>
<br>
Arcane could be split into the basic casting skills, <br>
Abjuration<br>
Conjuration<br>
Divination<br>
Enchantments<br>
Evocation<br>
<br>
But I would probably try to limit it to 3 subs as well.  Perhaps :<br>
Evocations (making things go boom!)<br>
Enchantments (Changing existing things properties)Conjurations (making useful things out of nothing) <br>
<br>
Wizards : Strong Nukes, weak pets (or none!), mixed utility<br>
Evoke (2)<br>
Enchant (3)<br>
Conjure (4)<br>
<br>
Mages : Great pets, OK nukes, mixed/weak utility<br>
